Figures Outputs

Fig. 1 The amount of cover area that is is water shallower then the cutoff (0.5 m) for the level of flows present in the simulation.



Fig. 2 The predation rating map. This map shows the extent to which the preatotors selected (bass, pikeminnow) for this model will be attracted to areas. The attraction is abase on the average of the conditions in each area over the entire extent the the run (i.e.the start (10/01/1982) and end (10/15/1982) dates of the daily environmental conditions input file).



Fig. 3 The fraction of an area that is undercover separated by sections that are on average above or bellow the depth and velocity cutoffs (0.5 m and 0.61 m/s respectively).



Fig. 4 The density histograms of the area that is undercover separated by sections that are on average above or bellow the depth and velocity cutoffs (0.5 m and 0.61 m/s respectively).



Fig. 5 A heat map showing the fraction of area at set average depths and velocities over the time of the simulation (10/01/1982 to 10/15/1982) .



Fig. 6 A set of maps showing the metabolic rate for both the juvenile and adult life stage of the simulated species of fish (chinook, green_sturgeon) if the fish swam at the water velocity and temperature of the cell for 24 hours.



The net energy of the fish.

Fig. 7 A set of maps showing the net energy budget for both the juvenile and adult life stage of the simulated species of fish (chinook, green_sturgeon) if the fish swam at the water velocity and temperature of the cell for 24 hours and consumed food.



Fig. 8 A set of maps showing the mortality rate for the juvenile life stage (represented by fish of length 5, 13 cm) of the fish species (chinook, green_sturgeon).
